Author-Name: Enrique G. Mendoza  
Title: Sudden Stops, Financial Crises, and Leverage 
Abstract:
 Financial crashes were followed by deep recessions in the Sudden Stops of
 emerging economies. An equilibrium business cycle model with a collateral 
 constraint explains this phenomenon as a result of the amplification and
 asymmetry that the constraint induces in the responses of macro-aggregates
 to  shocks. Leverage rises during expansions, and when it rises enough it
 triggers the constraint, causing a Fisherian deflation that reduces credit
 and the price and quantity of collateral assets. Output and factor
 allocations fall because access to working capital financing is also
 reduced. Precautionary saving makes Sudden Stops low probability events
 nested within normal cycles, as observed in the data. (JEL E21, E23, E32,
 E44, G01, O11, O16)
