Author-Name: Michael E. Waugh  
Title: International Trade and Income Differences 
Abstract:
 I develop a novel view of the trade frictions between rich and poor
 countries by arguing that to reconcile bilateral trade volumes and price
 data within a standard gravity model, the trade frictions between rich and
 poor countries must be systematically asymmetric, with poor countries
 facing higher costs to export relative to rich countries. I provide a
 method to model these asymmetries and demonstrate the merits of my
 approach relative to alternatives in the trade literature. I then argue
 that these trade frictions are quantitatively important to understanding
 the large differences in standards of living and total factor 
 productivity across countries. (JEL F11, F13, F14, O19 )
